etymologies: Middle English; earliest use found in Subsidy Roll, Leicestershire. Alteration of coroner, after crown

notes.text: Now regional or with allusion to Hamlet (see quots. 1604 1604)

etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in Promptorium Parvulorum. Partly from crown + -er

definitions: A person who crowns someone or something.
A heavy fall, especially (more fully "imperial crowner") one in which the person lands on his or her head. Now somewhat dated.

etymologies: early 17th century; earliest use found in Diurnal of Remarkable Occurrents. Alteration of colonel, after crown

definitions: A military commander, a colonel; specifically the commander of troops raised in one county.
